# Fitness / Health Tracker — checklist

Full rubric: Canvas (“Project Deliverable Latest_GRAD”). **Do the top sections first**; completed work is archived at the bottom.

---

## What to do next (in rough order)

### 1. Report (PDF)

- [x] README content in report: install steps, libs, versions, expected paths
- [x] Technical specifications (stack, frameworks)
- [ ] Conceptual design: ERD in **UML**
- [x] Logical design: crow’s foot (e.g. Workbench reverse engineer)
- [x] User activity / flow (text or diagram)
- [x] Lessons learned + future work (note anything broken, if applicable)
- [ ] File name: `canvas_group_name_final_report.pdf`

**Check:** PDF has every section; diagrams match submitted schema.

### 2. Video / presentation (5–7 min)

- [ ] Schema, architecture, and app purpose (audio/video clear)
- [ ] **Three** CRUD demos (or two if syllabus allows): DB **before** → app → DB **after**, change visible
- [ ] All group members participate; logical flow

**Check:** Dry run with timer; one practice watch-through.

### 3. Submission package

- [ ] Zip: `groupname_project.zip` — schema dump, app code, report (and extras if any)
- [ ] Submission note includes **project video link** (if required)
- [ ] Grader can build/run from **README only** (no missing files)

**Before you zip (delete from repo copy if you want a smaller submission):**  
`tests/` and `sql/sample_queries.sql` are optional — fine to drop if the rubric doesn’t ask for them. If you remove `tests/`, consider removing `pytest` from `requirements.txt` so graders aren’t confused.

**Grader / MySQL sanity checks (not in README on purpose):**  
- Submit **`.env.example`**, not `.env` (no real passwords).  
- `MYSQL_DATABASE` in `.env` must match `fitness_db` from `schema.sql`.  
- Data lives on the **MySQL server** — closing Workbench doesn’t delete it. Re-running **`schema.sql`** does wipe the DB. Refreshing the browser is normal; demos usually show rows in Workbench before/after using the app.

**Check:** Unzip elsewhere; README-only import DB + run app.

### 4. Rubric pass (Canvas — still open)

**Video / deliverable meta**

- [ ] Data schema described (logical design matches data)
- [ ] CRUD demo + verification in a second client
- [ ] Application functionality described
- [ ] Presentation quality (see/hear/follow)
- [ ] Group participation
- [ ] Logical flow of video

**Submission**

- [ ] Complete: DB objects + frontend + runnable dump + sample data + README; no post-deadline rescue

**Report criteria**

- [ ] Conceptual (UML) and logical (crow’s foot) designs
- [ ] Document structure
- [ ] Lessons learned + future work
- [ ] User activity description
- [ ] README + technical description sections

**Bonus (optional)**

- [ ] Any planned bonus items documented/demonstrated

---

## Done (archive)

### Cleanup

- [x] Remove unused files, dead code, and dependencies not needed for submission

### Database (MySQL)

- [x] Every foreign key specifies `ON UPDATE` and `ON DELETE`
- [x] Table count meets group size (1→≥6, 2→≥9, 3→≥12); schema in 3NF
- [x] Primary keys on all tables; FKs (and UNIQUE where needed) match ERD
- [x] Field/table constraints: NOT NULL, DEFAULT, etc., where appropriate
- [x] Server-side objects: procedures, functions, triggers (add event only if rubric requires)
- [x] Self-contained setup: `schema.sql` → `seed.sql` → `procedures.sql` on fresh MySQL

### Client application

- [x] **CREATE** — new rows persist (Workbench/CLI)
- [x] **READ** — data from DB
- [x] **UPDATE** — changes persist after refresh/reconnect
- [x] **DELETE** — rows removed in DB
- [x] UI: clear prompts and feedback; user-driven flow
- [x] Modularity: services + stored procedures; lean client SQL
- [x] Error handling: bad input / DB errors without crashing the app

### Wrap-up

- [x] Front-end polish and remaining UI work
- [x] Debug open issues
- [x] Final local verification (app + DB + `pytest`)

### Rubric — DB criteria (done)

- [x] Complexity / 3NF / minimum tables
- [x] PKs and FKs complete
- [x] FKs fully specified (`ON UPDATE` / `ON DELETE`)
- [x] Field and table constraints
- [x] Database programming objects

### Rubric — Client criteria (done)

- [x] CRUD coverage across entities/tables
- [x] User interface usability
- [x] CREATE / READ / UPDATE / DELETE as defined
- [x] Modularity (host language + DB objects)
- [x] Robustness / error handling
